Hi Thi, Karthik, all,

Thank you for spelling out the four possession-side rows. I agree that rows
1-4 should remain a substrate and authorize nothing by themselves. I
attached a short review and test-vector plan.

Three corrections are important before treating the rows as a verifier
contract:

   - Row 1 must be limited to attested inputs that are actually measured
   and bound to the enrolled key and enrollment record. Key existence alone=
 is
   not evidence for every claimed input.
   - Row 3 should enumerate the monitored conditions, detection timing, and
   the governed key operations. Key erasure protects the next relevant key =
use
   or agreement; an established connection still needs its own stated
   management rule.
   - Row 4 needs a re-assessment lease or expiry, delivery and clock
   assumptions, and a grace policy. Non-delivery does not fail closed merel=
y
   by being called non-delivery; after the lease, the next governed key use
   must fail because current status cannot be established.

The attached vectors cover enrollment binding, live possession, local
failure before and after a connection, lifecycle delivery, lease expiry,
and replay/stale/wrong-device events. The proposed outcome labels are
vector vocabulary only, not a request for new wire-level errors.

Best,
Songbo

On Tue, 14 Jul 2026 18:45:07 +0000, Thi Nguyen-Huu thi.nh@winmagic.com
wrote:

Karthik, Songbo, all,

To Morgan on the weekend I said I would state the possession-side rows in
Songbo=E2=80=99s template, and here they are.

The possession row is one of four that belong together. Possession is what
a verifier checks, but it is not self-supporting: Row 1 says why the key
means anything; Row 3 says
why its continued existence is an assertion and not an assumption; Row 4
says what happens when the condition is decided somewhere the endpoint
cannot see. Together they are one substrate =E2=80=94 they establish who is=
 present
and sound, and they authorize nothing.
Rows five through seven authorize, join on the action digest per Songbo=E2=
=80=99s
framing, and no row inherits another=E2=80=99s guarantees.

Row 2 is stated below for continuity with the three that surround it. Where
it differs from the reconciled text you have already recorded, yours stands=
.

Row 1 =E2=80=94 Enrollment binding (key, actor, workload, environment).

Claim: this key was built inside this hardware anchor, for this actor and
workload, with the required conditions as inputs to the build =E2=80=94 the=
 key
exists, therefore the inputs existed at mint.

Carrier: attestation evidence at enrollment; the platform key endorsed, the
public key registered with the verifier =E2=80=94 as a raw public key (RFC =
7250) or
in a certificate where one is wanted.

Verifier and rule: the credential service appraises the attestation at
issuance and pins the key. The binding is proven by attestation, not
asserted by the workload.

Binding and freshness: established at mint; re-appraisal per policy.
Attestation proves construction and custody at mint =E2=80=94 it does not p=
rove
future soundness. That is Rows 2=E2=80=934.

Failure behavior: failed appraisal, no enrollment; nothing exists to
present later.

Dependency: the hardware anchor (TPM, secure element, vTPM) and its
endorsement chain.

Evidence: the attestation record at enrollment.

Row 2 =E2=80=94 Live key possession at connection.

Claim: the presenter on this connection holds and can use the enrolled key
now. The key exists in exactly one place; validity is the successful use.

Carrier: the mTLS handshake itself. No new wire format.

Verifier and rule: standard TLS client authentication against the enrolled
key.

Binding and freshness: fresh per handshake, channel-bound; nothing bearer,
nothing replayable.

Failure behavior: key absent or unusable, the handshake fails. Fails closed
with no signal.

Dependency: Row 1 for what the key means. Nothing else =E2=80=94 this row l=
eans on
no other row.

Evidence: the connection itself; none retained, by design. Durable evidence
of a decision is Row 7=E2=80=99s job, not this row=E2=80=99s.

Row 3 =E2=80=94 Local condition failure / key unavailability.

Claim: the key=E2=80=99s continued existence is itself the assertion that t=
he mint
conditions still hold. When a locally visible condition fails =E2=80=94 the=
 user
departs, posture drops, protection is disabled in place, the workload ends
=E2=80=94 the platform erases the key in real
time.

Carrier: none. Absence is the carrier; no message is sent.

Verifier and rule: the verifier observes nothing except that Row 2 stops
succeeding. There is nothing to fetch and no list to distribute.

Binding and freshness: real-time at the endpoint; enforcement lands at the
key=E2=80=99s next use. An established connection can outlive a mid-session=
 failure
=E2=80=94 bounding connection lifetime is the fix, and it is the same fix r=
otation
needs for the same gap.

Failure behavior: fail-stop by absence. Zero-message revocation for the
locally visible class.

Dependency: Row 1=E2=80=99s anchor, and the property that the key is availa=
ble
nowhere else =E2=80=94 hardware holds that property for the key=E2=80=99s l=
ife; software
holds it only briefly.

Evidence: none, by design; the diagnostic is possession ceasing. The
condition inputs are software-observed posture readings feeding
hardware-held keys =E2=80=94 deterministic cryptography on sensor-grade inp=
uts,
stated here so the cell is honest.

Row 4 =E2=80=94 External lifecycle events.

Claim: conditions decided where the endpoint cannot see them =E2=80=94 a ro=
le
removed, a workload no longer trusted, quarantine, retirement =E2=80=94 are=
 carried
as an event to the platform, which erases the key. An external decision
becomes Row 3=E2=80=99s local absence: one event
per device, and the fan-out to relying parties happens by absence rather
than by notification.

Carrier: a continuous-evaluation event (CAEP / Shared Signals); one event
type, aligned with the naming in Iman=E2=80=99s drafts.

Verifier and rule: the relying party=E2=80=99s check remains Row 2; nothing=
 is
distributed per relying party.

Binding and freshness: bound at delivery. Where the device is unreachable,
the key=E2=80=99s liveness requirement fails closed =E2=80=94 no re-assessm=
ent within the
window, no key.

Failure behavior: fail closed on non-delivery.

Dependency: a signals channel to the platform, and Row 3=E2=80=99s erasure
mechanism.

Evidence: the event record at the transmitter.

Two seams to the authorizing rows, offered rather than claimed: Row 2 is
the possession dependency the mapping=E2=80=99s R4 names, and the endpoint =
platform
is a candidate for the
trusted display surface Row 7=E2=80=99s rendering residual asks for. Test v=
ectors
for Rows 2 and 3 to follow to the list.

Cheers

Thi

