<div dir=3D"ltr"><p>Hi Thi, Karthik, all,</p>
<p>Thank you for spelling out the four possession-side rows. I agree that r=
ows 1-4 should remain a substrate and authorize nothing by themselves. I at=
tached a short review and test-vector plan.</p>
<p>Three corrections are important before treating the rows as a verifier c=
ontract:</p>
<ul>
<li>Row 1 must be limited to attested inputs that are actually measured and=
 bound to the enrolled key and enrollment record. Key existence alone is no=
t evidence for every claimed input.</li>
<li>Row 3 should enumerate the monitored conditions, detection timing, and =
the governed key operations. Key erasure protects the next relevant key use=
 or agreement; an established connection still needs its own stated managem=
ent rule.</li>
<li>Row 4 needs a re-assessment lease or expiry, delivery and clock assumpt=
ions, and a grace policy. Non-delivery does not fail closed merely by being=
 called non-delivery; after the lease, the next governed key use must fail =
because current status cannot be established.</li>
</ul>
<p>The attached vectors cover enrollment binding, live possession, local fa=
ilure before and after a connection, lifecycle delivery, lease expiry, and =
replay/stale/wrong-device events. The proposed outcome labels are vector vo=
cabulary only, not a request for new wire-level errors.</p>
<p>Best,<br>
Songbo</p>
<p>On Tue, 14 Jul 2026 18:45:07 +0000, Thi Nguyen-Huu <a href=3D"mailto:thi=
